These Impala are part of a free-living population of about 600 that roam across 4 adjacent cattle farms, hemmed in on two opposing sides by game fences, with the Limpopo River on the third side and access to communal grazing areas, cattle post settlements and the local village in the 4th direction. It has been observed that in a breeding group a dominant female tends to take the lead with the other females fanning out around and behind her as they browse and the herd sire is stationed in the rear from which position he can keep an eye on all members of his harem and also see any approaching intruders; every so often he can be observed to gather the spreading females up into a tighter group</p>												2015-07-23							2015-07-23																BW	Central				Dovedale Farm: cattle ranch											-23.5528	27.0817		1																																			24620136				2018-04-17T14:01:05Z			<h4>Impala</h4><br> Confidence: As sure as can be; Reputation Score = 1.9623 EE; Is_Likely = True;<br><strong>Notes:</strong> 3 black stripes on tail and back of thighs, black ^ankles^	147920								Aepyceros melampus melampus								Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Artiodactyla	Bovidae	Aepyceros				subspecies
